## 3. Safe{Wallet} as the Operator Layer

### 3.1 Why Safe

Safe (formerly Gnosis Safe) is the most battle-tested smart account
infrastructure on Ethereum. It provides M-of-N multisig, modular architecture
(modules, guards, fallback handlers), ERC-4337 account abstraction, and
formal verification of core contracts. Over $60B in assets are secured by
Safe contracts.

### 3.2 Safe Deployment (Per Fleet)

Each fleet deploys one Safe{Wallet} that serves as the operator authority for
all robots in that fleet:

```json
{
  "safe_address": "0xFleetSafe",
  "chain_id": 8453,
  "owners": [
    "0xFleetManager",
    "0xSecurityOfficer",
    "0xFieldTechnician"
  ],
  "threshold": 2,
  "modules": ["0xFleetPolicyServerModule"],
  "guard": "0xFleetActionGuard",
  "fallback_handler": "0xSafe4337Module"
}
```

### 3.3 Safe Owners = Operator Keys

Each Safe owner corresponds to an operator role. Owners can sign from any
device — hardware wallet, mobile app, browser extension, or passkeys. Safe
collects signatures asynchronously until the threshold is met.

| Owner | Role | Signing Method | Authority |
|-------|------|---------------|-----------|
| 0xFleetManager | Fleet Manager | Ledger / Air-gapped ESP32 | Tier 2: firmware, autonomous mode, fleet ops |
| 0xSecurityOfficer | Security Officer | Ledger / Safe mobile app | Tier 3: revocation, policy changes, emergency |
| 0xFieldTechnician | Field Technician | Safe mobile app with passkeys | Tier 2: maintenance, recalibration |

### 3.4 Owner Management

Adding, removing, or replacing operators is a Safe transaction:

```
// Add a new operator
safe.addOwnerWithThreshold(newOwner, newThreshold)

// Remove an operator
safe.removeOwner(prevOwner, owner, newThreshold)

// Swap an operator (atomic)
safe.swapOwner(prevOwner, oldOwner, newOwner)
```

All owner changes require the current threshold of signatures. The Safe
address remains the same — so the ERC-8004 registration doesn't need
updating when operators rotate.

