## 4. Fleet Policy Server as Safe Module

### 4.1 Module Architecture

In v0.0.1, the fleet server held its own secp256k1 private key and cosigned
requests independently. In v0.0.2, the server becomes a **Safe Module** — a
smart contract that is authorized to execute transactions through the Safe,
but only within constraints defined by the Guard.

```solidity
// FleetPolicyServerModule.sol (simplified)

contract FleetPolicyServerModule {
    address public safe;
    address public server;  // The fleet server's EOA

    modifier onlyServer() {
        require(msg.sender == server, "Not server");
        _;
    }

    /// @notice Execute a Tier 0/1 action on behalf of the fleet Safe
    /// @dev Guard contract validates action before execution
    function executeAutomatedAction(
        address robot,
        bytes32 actionHash,
        uint8 actionTier,
        bytes calldata data
    ) external onlyServer {
        // The Safe's Guard will check:
        // - actionTier <= 1 (module can only do Tier 0/1)
        // - rate limits haven't been exceeded
        // - robot is registered and not quarantined

        ISafe(safe).execTransactionFromModule(
            /* to */ address(this),
            /* value */ 0,
            /* data */ data,
            /* operation */ Enum.Operation.Call
        );
    }
}
```

### 4.2 What the Module Can and Cannot Do

| Can Do | Cannot Do |
|--------|-----------|
| Execute Tier 0/1 actions that pass the Guard | Execute Tier 2/3 actions (Guard rejects) |
| Auto-cosign telemetry, heartbeat, micropayments | Approve firmware updates or autonomous mode |
| Respond to robot requests within policy | Initiate actions without a robot request |
| Be revoked by Safe owners at any time | Resist revocation or modify its own permissions |

### 4.3 Module Revocation

If the fleet server is compromised, Safe owners revoke the module:

```
// Disable the compromised module
safe.disableModule(prevModule, fleetPolicyServerModule)

// Deploy and enable a new module
safe.enableModule(newFleetPolicyServerModule)
```

This requires the Safe threshold (e.g., 2-of-3 owners). No server key
rotation needed — the module is permissioned by the Safe, not by a private
key.

