## 5. Safe Guard: FleetActionGuard

### 5.1 Purpose

The Guard is an on-chain smart contract that validates every transaction the
Safe executes — whether initiated by owners (Tier 2/3) or by the module
(Tier 0/1). It provides a second layer of policy enforcement that cannot be
bypassed by server compromise.

### 5.2 Guard Contract (Simplified)

```solidity
// FleetActionGuard.sol

contract FleetActionGuard is BaseGuard {

    struct ActionPolicy {
        uint8 maxModuleTier;
        uint256 dailySpendLimit;
        uint256 dailySpent;
        uint256 lastResetTimestamp;
        mapping(address => bool) quarantinedRobots;
    }

    ActionPolicy public policy;

    function checkTransaction(
        address to,
        uint256 value,
        bytes memory data,
        Enum.Operation operation,
        uint256 safeTxGas,
        uint256 baseGas,
        uint256 gasPrice,
        address gasToken,
        address payable refundReceiver,
        bytes memory signatures,
        address msgSender
    ) external override {

        // If called by module (automated action)
        if (isModule(msgSender)) {
            (address robot, uint8 actionTier) =
                decodeAction(data);

            // Module can only do Tier 0/1
            require(
                actionTier <= policy.maxModuleTier,
                "Tier too high for module"
            );

            // Robot must not be quarantined
            require(
                !policy.quarantinedRobots[robot],
                "Robot quarantined"
            );

            // Check daily spending limit
            if (value > 0) {
                _resetDailyIfNeeded();
                require(
                    policy.dailySpent + value
                        <= policy.dailySpendLimit,
                    "Daily spend limit exceeded"
                );
                policy.dailySpent += value;
            }
        }

        // If called by owners (Tier 2/3), no additional
        // restrictions — M-of-N threshold enforced by Safe
    }

    function checkAfterExecution(
        bytes32, bool
    ) external override {
        // Post-execution checks if needed
    }
}
```

### 5.3 Guard vs Server Policy

| Check | Server (off-chain) | Guard (on-chain) |
|-------|-------------------|------------------|
| Rate limits (per-second/minute) | Yes (Redis) | No (gas-prohibitive) |
| Geofencing | Yes (GPS validation) | No (no oracle) |
| Firmware attestation | Yes (hash comparison) | No (complex computation) |
| Daily spending cap | Yes (redundant) | Yes (authoritative) |
| Action tier enforcement | Yes (redundant) | Yes (authoritative) |
| Robot quarantine | Yes (Redis flag) | Yes (authoritative) |
| Time-of-day restrictions | Yes (timezone logic) | Possible (block.timestamp) |

The server handles high-frequency, complex checks (rate limits, geofences,
attestation). The Guard handles low-frequency, critical checks (spending
caps, tier enforcement, quarantine) as the authoritative on-chain backstop.

